            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> _why_ exactly is the legacy matchparen slow? what are the _specific_ fixes you made for each pitfall?\n\nI partly explaned this in the initial post.\nFor regex syntax files - bottleneck is `synstack()` could be slow to check with each `skip()` function of `searchpair()` function, which itself is slow compare to my custom implementation https://github.com/monkoose/matchparen.nvim/blob/main/lua/matchparen/search.lua (it also \"properly\" skips folds, so it's implementation a little bit longer that I would like). There is almost nothing else you can do, unless you speed up `synstack()`.\n\nFor `:syntax off` - bottleneck is `searchpair()`, not sure why. Bad implementation? Or luajit's `string.find` is that much faster, which is used internally in matchparen.nvim. It is just assumption. You can test it yourself and see how faster it actually is without syntax highlighting matchparen.nvim compare to other matchparen implementations which are using `searchpair()`.\n\nFor treesitter I'm implementing caching of the skipped nodes processing each line in one go\nhttps://github.com/monkoose/matchparen.nvim/blob/33703b64f0f4941b5b6179131a13bfb86eba414e/lua/matchparen/treesitter.lua#L21-L31 unlike current implementation https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/7b46848f140285be586cc3946db6976bd6bed2a5/runtime/lua/nvim/matchparen.lua#L172-L179 which on each `skip()` function retriggers whole node searching again. Thats why I think matchparen.nvim that much faster in treesitter highlighted buffers.\n\nUnless I would see real interest on improving matchparen speed from core devs, that will also require for them to test my examples, I would not start to work on PR. I'm happy user of my plugin for a long time and it would require some time and effort to make it compatible with neovim standards. \nOr someone could take inspiration from my plugin and also improve some parts, because I'm definitely not the best programmer.",
